      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot garden ¶ 1/12/71. ¶  ¶ Since I wrote last, dear Dr Hooker, I was able to secure yet for the Niagara stems of ¶  ¶ Dicksonia squarrosa ¶  ¶ Cyathea dealbata [&amp;]...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">71.12.01c</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, ff. 27-8<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">1/12/71.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since I wrote last, dear Dr Hooker, I was able to secure yet for the Niagara stems of</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dicksonia squarrosa</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Cyathea dealbata [&amp;]</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Cyathea Smithii,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">of which you can have one stem of each for Kew and one for Mr Booth of Flottbeck, if you desire it.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hooker, 5 November 1871.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will also get by the Niagara<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">gigantic</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>stems of Dicksonia antarctica and one very tall one of Alsophila Australis, if you value them for Kew or Flottbeck.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Captain of the Niagra<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Niagara.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>has fine accommodation for these stems and will water them on the voyage. He retains some himself for the owners of the ship, and the rest of these ferns got thus a free passage. You are entitled to select the largest specimens.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Lately the large Iridea of Lord Howe's Island has flowered. It proves a new Iris of the section Moraea, which I have named Iris (Moraea) Robinsonii in honor of my friend Sir Hercules Robinson, the Governor of Ceylon, who is promoted lately to the Governor Ship of N.S. Wales. Hence this Iris belongs to his territory now. It is in flower much like Iris compressa Thunb., on which Linné founded his genus Moraea, but the leaves and stem are as large as that of Phormium! To me it seems clear, That Kers &amp; Endlichers genus Moraea, (but not Thunbergs) must fall together with Iris, by which means we obtain a very natural genus, ranging still wider then Sisyrinchium.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M named<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Iris robinsoniana</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in B71.12.03, p. 153-4, citing it also as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Moraea robinsoniana</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>under the joint authority of himself and Charles Moore. Bentham (1863-78) vol. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>6, p. 409, rejected M's uniting<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Moraea</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>with<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Iris</seg>, and listed it<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">as M. robinsoniana</seg>.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Klatts notes on the S. African Irideae<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Probably in the series of papers in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Linnaea</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>culminating in Klatt (1866). In B65.10.01, p. 21, M records having volumes of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Linnaea</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>only for 1847–57.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I have not yet seen. Our late lamented friend, Prof Harvey, never likely entering on a comparison of Iris &amp; Moraea, keeps in your edition of his genera only Moraea up.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Harvey (1868), p. 372.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have established also a new genus of Saxifrageae from Lord Howes Island, namely Colmeiroa,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M erected<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Colmeiroa</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">C. carpodetoides</seg>), in B71.12.03, p. 149.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>next to Carpodetus, but the cells are one<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>seeded, &amp; it is differing also in some other respect Colmeiroa of Reuter is not upheld by [J] Müller as you know.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Reuter's genus<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Colmeiroa</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(Euphorbiaceae) was established in 1843, but<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>J.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Müller (1866), p. 448, treated it as a synonym of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Fluggeae</seg>, erected in 1805.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There are several other plants from Ld Howes Island, which I have examined for the current number of the Fragmenta, which is to appear this month.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B71.12.03.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>But what is this to the treasures of the wonderland New Guinea!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For the first time since 1847, I have no letters by mail from Europe through the sinking of the Rangoon at Ceylon.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Rangoon</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>struck a rock while leaving Galle Harbour, Ceylon, on 1 November: 'All lives were saved, but the whole of the Australian mails, the cargo and the passengers' baggage were lost' (<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 27 November 1871 p. 5).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I trust, that all my friends &amp; correspondents will repeat in their next months letter, what they wrote &amp; send duplicates of any prints lost with the wreck at Point d[e] Gall[e].</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Possibly Mr Bentham may have written to obtain new material; so he must kindly repeat his wishes.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The loss of Sir Rod. Murchison is a sad one to Geography &amp; Geology.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Murchison died on 22 October 1871.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>To me he always proved a kind condescending friend. I wished he could have lived to see Livingstone return, if indeed that brave man will really ever see civilisation again.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Murchison<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1864-5): the Royal Geographical Society had engaged Livingstone 'once more to revisit Southeastern Africa, and determine the hidden watershed of that vast country' (p. 249) where, 'in addition to his efforts as a Geographer [he] … will act as a pioneer in removing those obstacles which at present render the traveling of Christian missionaries … fraught with disaster and profitless suffering' (p. 264). Livingstone was still in the field at the time M wrote (see Livingstone's 1871 field diary, http://livingstone.library.ucla.edu/1871diary/index.htm, accessed 18 January 2014).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Always yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">The Captain has 2 tall Alsophilas from me. Perhaps he would spare one for Mr Booth, and take an other Dicksonia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Australian Eclipse Expedition may bring a few new plants from Cape Sidmouth.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn11" n="12">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A total solar eclipse occurred in the far north of Australia on 11 December 1871. The Sydney and Melbourne Observatories collaborated in sending a party to Torres Strait to view the event.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I am promoting also, indeed called forth Mr Giles Expedition from the S. Austr telegraph line to West Australia, probably the River Murchison.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn12" n="13">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ernest<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Giles's<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>1872 expedition from 23 August to 18 November 1872 was blocked by lack of water and the salt pans of Lake Amadeus. See B75.04.07<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>E.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Giles<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1875).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Alsophila Australis</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
